Phase 2: Firewall & Network Security Fundamentals (Weeks 5–8)
Goal: Learn firewall basics, VPNs, and security monitoring.

Week 5: Firewalls
Theory:
What is a firewall? Packet filtering vs Stateful
Fortinet/Cisco/Palo Alto firewall basics
Security zones and policies

Lab:
Configure a basic FortiGate firewall
config system interface
    edit "port1"
        set ip 192.168.1.1/24
        set allowaccess ping https ssh
    next
end

config firewall policy
    edit 1
        set srcintf "port1"
        set dstintf "port2"
        set srcaddr "all"
        set dstaddr "all"
        set action accept
    next
end


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Scenario

Two SRX devices: SRX1 and SRX2

Each SRX has:

ge-0/0/0 interface connected to a common subnet (e.g., 10.0.0.0/30)

Each SRX will advertise loopback networks via BGP.

Device	Interface	IP Address	Loopback
SRX1	ge-0/0/0	10.0.0.1/30	1.1.1.1/32
SRX2	ge-0/0/0	10.0.0.2/30	2.2.2.2/32

AS numbers:

SRX1: 65001

SRX2: 65002

Step 1: Configure basic interfaces

On SRX1:

set interfaces ge-0/0/0 unit 0 family inet address 10.0.0.1/30

On SRX2:

set interfaces ge-0/0/0 unit 0 family inet address 10.0.0.2/30

Explanation:

unit 0 is the default logical interface.

family inet is for IPv4 addresses.

Step 2: Configure loopbacks

On SRX1:

set interfaces lo0 unit 0 family inet address 1.1.1.1/32

On SRX2:

set interfaces lo0 unit 0 family inet address 2.2.2.2/32

Explanation:
Loopbacks are used as stable BGP router IDs and for advertising reachable networks.

Step 3: Configure BGP
SRX1 (AS 65001)
set routing-options router-id 1.1.1.1
set protocols bgp group SRX2 type external
set protocols bgp group SRX2 peer-as 65002
set protocols bgp group SRX2 neighbor 10.0.0.2
set protocols bgp group SRX2 export EXPORT-LO


SRX2 (AS 65002)

set routing-options router-id 2.2.2.2
set protocols bgp group SRX1 type external
set protocols bgp group SRX1 peer-as 65001
set protocols bgp group SRX1 neighbor 10.0.0.1
set protocols bgp group SRX1 export EXPORT-LO


Explanation:

router-id: identifies the BGP router uniquely (commonly loopback IP).

group: logical grouping of BGP neighbors.

type external: indicates eBGP.

peer-as: remote AS number.

neighbor: the IP address of the BGP peer.

export: optional policy to advertise networks.

Step 4: Create a policy to advertise loopbacks

On both SRXs:

set policy-options policy-statement EXPORT-LO term 1 from interface lo0.0
set policy-options policy-statement EXPORT-LO term 1 then accept


Explanation:

BGP does not advertise any network by default.

Policy statement EXPORT-LO tells BGP to advertise the loopback interface (lo0).

Step 5: Commit the configuration
commit

Step 6: Verify BGP

On either SRX:

show bgp summary
show route protocol bgp


Expected output:

BGP session should be Established.

Loopback network of the peer should appear in the routing table.

Step 7: Optional: Test connectivity

From SRX1:

ping 2.2.2.2


From SRX2:

ping 1.1.1.1


If everything is configured correctly, the pings should succeed.

✅ Key Notes for EVE-NG:

Ensure SRX VM interfaces are connected to the same virtual network.

Use Ctrl+Shift+6 in the console if pinging from EVE-NG doesn’t show traffic.

Juniper SRX runs JUNOS, so commit is required after configuration changes.

By default, BGP will not advertise anything unless a policy is applied.

If you want, I can draw a ready-to-use EVE-NG topology diagram with all SRX nodes, links, IPs, and BGP settings, so you can just drag and drop it and configure. This makes labs much faster.

